00:10:56.750 --> 00:10:59.780
Most of the microbial
diversity of the biosphere

00:10:59.780 --> 00:11:01.880
is unexplored, untapped.

00:11:01.880 --> 00:11:04.140
Those microbes are
uncultured in the lab.

00:11:04.140 --> 00:11:07.030
We really don't
understand them very well.

00:11:07.030 --> 00:11:09.310
We've only poked
around the solar system

00:11:09.310 --> 00:11:11.050
with our robotic
and remote sensing

00:11:11.050 --> 00:11:13.210
probes in a few locations.

00:11:13.210 --> 00:11:16.630
We have explored or even
diagnosed in the simplest way

00:11:16.630 --> 00:11:20.280
a tiny fraction of the habitable
real estate in the Milky Way

00:11:20.280 --> 00:11:21.400
galaxy.

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:23.900
And the activity of
SETI, the abbreviation

00:11:23.900 --> 00:11:26.630
for the Search for
Extraterrestrial Intelligence,

00:11:26.630 --> 00:11:29.800
is in its infancy, and
as they would admit,

00:11:29.800 --> 00:11:31.720
have only searched
a tiny fraction

00:11:31.720 --> 00:11:34.480
of all the possible
stars that could have

00:11:34.480 --> 00:11:36.810
planets sending signals to us.

00:11:36.810 --> 00:11:40.660
So this is a subject where we're
just starting to get going.

00:11:40.660 --> 00:11:43.410
The context for life in the
universe is fairly simple,

00:11:43.410 --> 00:11:47.450
and you've heard it built up
in stages in previous talks,

00:11:47.450 --> 00:11:51.644
the first part is, of course,
chemistry and also the fact

00:11:51.644 --> 00:11:53.435
that there are places
where life can exist.

00:11:56.040 --> 00:12:00.490
So we understand that as a
natural by product of star

00:12:00.490 --> 00:12:02.720
formation planets will form.

00:12:02.720 --> 00:12:05.660
It's an unexceptional
physical process.

00:12:05.660 --> 00:12:09.310
Collapsing clouds of gas
and dust form a disk.

00:12:09.310 --> 00:12:11.336
Most of the mass
goes into the star.

00:12:11.336 --> 00:12:15.430
A small fraction is left
over and forms rocky objects

00:12:15.430 --> 00:12:18.820
that glom together by accretion.

00:12:18.820 --> 00:12:21.790
Radiation from the young star
drives out the residual gas.

00:12:21.790 --> 00:12:23.710
And so you end up with
small rocky objects

00:12:23.710 --> 00:12:27.130
near the star and
larger, cooler objects,

00:12:27.130 --> 00:12:29.846
which can accrete gassy
envelopes further out.

00:12:29.846 --> 00:12:32.180
Those are the gas giants.

00:12:32.180 --> 00:12:34.510
Turns out that's maybe a
little bit of a just so

00:12:34.510 --> 00:12:36.260
story to explain
our solar system,

00:12:36.260 --> 00:12:39.010
because the planets we've
started to find elsewhere

00:12:39.010 --> 00:12:41.200
do not follow this
simple picture.

00:12:41.200 --> 00:12:43.490
But certainly we expect
planets to form naturally

00:12:43.490 --> 00:12:44.650
wherever stars form.

00:12:44.650 --> 00:12:47.020
And that's what
we've been finding.

00:12:47.020 --> 00:12:49.920
We also know that the
ingredients for life

00:12:49.920 --> 00:12:51.410
are widespread.

00:12:51.410 --> 00:12:54.060
So you might worry in the
business of astrobiology

00:12:54.060 --> 00:12:55.640
whether the
requirement that life

00:12:55.640 --> 00:13:00.180
be made with carbon and use
water is overly restrictive.

00:13:00.180 --> 00:13:01.330
And I would say, no.

00:13:01.330 --> 00:13:03.500
I would say we should
open our minds to life

00:13:03.500 --> 00:13:06.340
that doesn't have that basis.

00:13:06.340 --> 00:13:08.390
But there's no need
to look beyond that,

00:13:08.390 --> 00:13:10.110
because as you
can see, carbon is

00:13:10.110 --> 00:13:12.380
one of the most abundant
elements in the universe.

00:13:12.380 --> 00:13:13.560
Made in stars.

00:13:13.560 --> 00:13:16.290
Distributed into the
space between stars.

00:13:16.290 --> 00:13:20.220
The long journey of all the
carbon atoms in our bodies

00:13:20.220 --> 00:13:22.240
probably encompasses
dozens or even

00:13:22.240 --> 00:13:25.470
hundreds of generations
of stars over cosmic time,

00:13:25.470 --> 00:13:26.850
an extraordinary story.

00:13:26.850 --> 00:13:30.270
Each carbon atom has a
different story in fact.

00:13:30.270 --> 00:13:31.780
But the ingredient is there.

00:13:31.780 --> 00:13:33.890
And water is one of the
most abundant molecules

00:13:33.890 --> 00:13:34.990
in the universe.

00:13:34.990 --> 00:13:37.610
So even if we say that
life needs those things,

00:13:37.610 --> 00:13:40.350
that is not restrictive
in a cosmic sense.

00:13:40.350 --> 00:13:42.950
Also, the universe has been
getting more fit for life

00:13:42.950 --> 00:13:46.980
as cosmic time passes, because
stars have been progressively

00:13:46.980 --> 00:13:48.890
been making more carbon.

00:13:48.890 --> 00:13:51.940
And so the fact that we
live in an ancient universe

00:13:51.940 --> 00:13:55.520
should not surprise us because
we couldn't exist in a universe

00:13:55.520 --> 00:13:57.630
100 million years
after it formed,

00:13:57.630 --> 00:13:59.440
even though there
were stars then.

00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:02.450
They were pristine stars made
only of hydrogen and helium

00:14:02.450 --> 00:14:04.070
with no planets around them.

00:14:04.070 --> 00:14:06.690
There was no grit
to grow the pearl.

00:14:06.690 --> 00:14:08.810
And so back in
the early universe

00:14:08.810 --> 00:14:11.720
there probably was no life.

00:14:11.720 --> 00:14:13.190
So the ingredients
are widespread.

00:14:13.190 --> 00:14:16.176
And the ingredients
are put out there

00:14:16.176 --> 00:14:19.200
by cycles of star
birth and death.

00:14:19.200 --> 00:14:22.410
And you've heard some about
that in previous lecture.

00:14:22.410 --> 00:14:25.850
So these heavy elements are
cooked inside stars by fusion,

00:14:25.850 --> 00:14:28.270
are ejected into
interstellar space,

00:14:28.270 --> 00:14:31.280
where they become part of
a new generation of stars.

00:14:31.280 --> 00:14:34.230
And this cyclic process
of star birth and death,

00:14:34.230 --> 00:14:38.240
the creation of heavy elements
by fusion deep inside stars.

00:14:38.240 --> 00:14:40.990
Of course, all of
these fusion events

00:14:40.990 --> 00:14:43.460
happened at least 4 and
1/2 billion years ago

00:14:43.460 --> 00:14:45.030
because they preceded
the formation

00:14:45.030 --> 00:14:46.690
of the Earth and the sun.

00:14:46.690 --> 00:14:48.690
So this is a life
story of stars.

00:14:48.690 --> 00:14:50.630
But it's also our life story.

00:14:50.630 --> 00:14:53.530
It's the story of our
life, of our biology.

00:14:53.530 --> 00:14:54.680
And they couldn't exist.

00:14:54.680 --> 00:14:57.270
If stars were selfish and
hoarded their heavy elements

00:14:57.270 --> 00:14:59.920
in their cores and just
shrunk into stellar corpses

00:14:59.920 --> 00:15:02.887
with no return of heavy elements
to the universe at large,

00:15:02.887 --> 00:15:03.970
there would be no biology.

00:15:06.510 --> 00:15:08.070
Now we have an
immediate problem,

00:15:08.070 --> 00:15:10.730
and as a non-biologist,
it's easy for me

00:15:10.730 --> 00:15:12.560
to point to it very strongly.

00:15:12.560 --> 00:15:14.502
Biologists know what they study.

00:15:14.502 --> 00:15:16.460
But if we're talking
about life in the universe

00:15:16.460 --> 00:15:19.160
we're worrying about the
general case of something

00:15:19.160 --> 00:15:20.570
where we know one instance.

00:15:20.570 --> 00:15:22.750
And that's a difficult
position to be in.

00:15:22.750 --> 00:15:24.904
And defining life
is just difficult.

00:15:24.904 --> 00:15:26.820
For the professional
biologist it's difficult.

00:15:26.820 --> 00:15:29.620
For astrobiologist,
perhaps even more so.

00:15:29.620 --> 00:15:32.440
Because if you ask that life
have organizing principles

00:15:32.440 --> 00:15:34.995
and complex and interesting
behavior, you might imagine

00:15:34.995 --> 00:15:37.880
you know what biology
would look like sight

00:15:37.880 --> 00:15:40.590
unseen in another world,
but it's not obvious

00:15:40.590 --> 00:15:42.564
what it would look like.

00:15:42.564 --> 00:15:46.043
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:16:57.611 --> 00:17:00.093
[RUMBLING SOUND]

00:17:00.593 --> 00:17:04.310
So if we saw that happening on
the surface of an alien planet,

00:17:04.310 --> 00:17:06.230
we'd probably get quite excited.

00:17:06.230 --> 00:17:07.569
But there's no biology there.

00:17:07.569 --> 00:17:09.250
There's not even chemistry.

00:17:09.250 --> 00:17:10.869
That's just physics.

00:17:10.869 --> 00:17:15.530
That's just flour, water, a
pie tray, and a bass speaker.

00:17:15.530 --> 00:17:19.440
So we're trying to broaden
the envelope of biology.

00:17:19.440 --> 00:17:21.970
We don't yet know
whether, even where

00:17:21.970 --> 00:17:24.440
they're at the micro
level of the genetic code

00:17:24.440 --> 00:17:26.710
or at the macro level
of natural selection,

00:17:26.710 --> 00:17:29.420
biology operates anywhere
other than the Earth.

00:17:29.420 --> 00:17:31.830
We suppose and
hope that it might,

00:17:31.830 --> 00:17:33.620
because it will add
to our understanding

00:17:33.620 --> 00:17:35.380
when we discover
something interesting.

00:17:35.380 --> 00:17:39.130
But the truth is we have to be
open for other possibilities.

00:17:39.130 --> 00:17:41.040
And we have to play
this interesting game

00:17:41.040 --> 00:17:43.680
of asking about hypotheticals,
because those hypotheticals

00:17:43.680 --> 00:17:45.290
might exist in the universe.

00:17:45.290 --> 00:17:49.120
We have to ask what might be
and doesn't violate any laws

00:17:49.120 --> 00:17:52.160
of physics or chemistry or
even our knowledge of biology,

00:17:52.160 --> 00:17:52.740
but isn't.

00:17:52.740 --> 00:17:55.500
Things that could happen
but don't here but

00:17:55.500 --> 00:17:56.800
might happen elsewhere.

00:17:56.800 --> 00:17:59.480
That's a difficult thing to do.

00:17:59.480 --> 00:18:02.020
When we're starting with talking
about life in the universe,

00:18:02.020 --> 00:18:04.970
we have to be very clear
about what life on Earth is

00:18:04.970 --> 00:18:05.600
and isn't.

00:18:05.600 --> 00:18:08.970
Probably to non-biologist,
the most striking thing

00:18:08.970 --> 00:18:16.090
is that everything from a fungus
to a great whale to a butterfly

00:18:16.090 --> 00:18:17.070
is all one thing.

00:18:17.070 --> 00:18:19.000
Life on Earth is one thing.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:21.080
And that one thing has
the same genetic code,

00:18:21.080 --> 00:18:23.420
the same biochemical basis.

00:18:23.420 --> 00:18:25.590
And it's basis of course is DNA.

00:18:25.590 --> 00:18:28.480
The tree of life used to be
defined in terms of species.

00:18:28.480 --> 00:18:32.380
The diversity of species dating,
of course, back before Darwin.

00:18:32.380 --> 00:18:35.220
But the modern tree of life is
based on the genetic material.

00:18:35.220 --> 00:18:37.580
It's based on the
gradual divergence

00:18:37.580 --> 00:18:41.760
from a hypothetical last common
ancestor, perhaps 4 billion

00:18:41.760 --> 00:18:44.770
years ago on the Earth,
where time moves forward

00:18:44.770 --> 00:18:48.670
in the upward
direction, and where

00:18:48.670 --> 00:18:52.370
genetic diversity is represented
by distance along this tree.

00:18:52.370 --> 00:18:55.400
This is very different from a
tree of life based on species,

00:18:55.400 --> 00:18:58.680
because humans, if we
could put humans on this,

00:18:58.680 --> 00:19:03.720
we are smaller than the dot
on the eye of the animals.

00:19:03.720 --> 00:19:06.910
So we are the tiniest little
twiglet on the tree of life.

00:19:06.910 --> 00:19:09.890
And most of the real estate
of biological and genetic

00:19:09.890 --> 00:19:13.270
diversity and metabolic
diversity is in microorganisms.

00:19:13.270 --> 00:19:15.110
This is a microbial
world, and we

00:19:15.110 --> 00:19:18.630
our little outriggers, maybe
small, unlikely contingent

00:19:18.630 --> 00:19:19.950
outcomes of evolution.

00:19:19.950 --> 00:19:20.970
We don't know.

00:19:20.970 --> 00:19:23.300
But that's the way
the world looks.

00:19:23.300 --> 00:19:25.650
And so that's the context
for understanding life

00:19:25.650 --> 00:19:27.040
in the universe.

00:19:27.040 --> 00:19:29.250
This is quite surprising
at some level.

00:19:29.250 --> 00:19:33.020
We share this
percentage-- or these

00:19:33.020 --> 00:19:34.820
are the number of
deviant nucleic acid,

00:19:34.820 --> 00:19:37.270
so the amount of genetic
material overlap.

00:19:37.270 --> 00:19:39.320
And you may drink
your beer and think

00:19:39.320 --> 00:19:41.580
that it's just a nice beverage
and something that you

00:19:41.580 --> 00:19:42.490
relax with.

00:19:42.490 --> 00:19:46.460
But it actually has kinship with
you at almost the 50% level.

00:19:46.460 --> 00:19:49.430
So you are not that
different from your beer.

00:19:49.430 --> 00:19:52.720
And so it's striking that such
a small amount of difference

00:19:52.720 --> 00:19:55.130
in genetic material--
it's no good

00:19:55.130 --> 00:19:57.290
playing the Guinness
Book of Records game.

00:19:57.290 --> 00:20:00.060
If you want to make us best
because we have more base pairs

00:20:00.060 --> 00:20:01.720
or more genes, it's not true.

00:20:01.720 --> 00:20:04.250
So you have to look somewhere
else for why we're special.

00:20:04.250 --> 00:20:06.580
So this becomes a context
for life in the universe

00:20:06.580 --> 00:20:09.930
too if what happened on
the Earth was not unusual.

00:20:09.930 --> 00:20:11.640
Now the very difficult
question of can

00:20:11.640 --> 00:20:13.870
we tell the story of how
life on Earth started?

00:20:13.870 --> 00:20:16.800
That, of course, would
be a whole lecture.

00:20:16.800 --> 00:20:17.810
It's not clear.

00:20:17.810 --> 00:20:20.760
We cannot connect all the
dots between the simple small

00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:23.960
molecules that were abundantly
available in interstellar space

00:20:23.960 --> 00:20:27.810
and on the primordial Earth to
the first cell or proto cell.

00:20:27.810 --> 00:20:28.760
We cannot.

00:20:28.760 --> 00:20:31.090
But in different
lab experiments,

00:20:31.090 --> 00:20:33.250
pieces of this story
have been told,

00:20:33.250 --> 00:20:37.110
even to the level of
self-catalyzing fragments

00:20:37.110 --> 00:20:40.670
of RNA to the spontaneous
formation of vessels that

00:20:40.670 --> 00:20:43.560
have some of the properties
of very small cells

00:20:43.560 --> 00:20:46.860
and to the creation of
small concentrated chemical

00:20:46.860 --> 00:20:48.736
reactors, which is
at some level what

00:20:48.736 --> 00:20:51.340
a cell is before it gets going.

00:20:51.340 --> 00:20:54.750
But none of these produce
replicating molecules that

00:20:54.750 --> 00:20:56.280
would hold the genetic code.

00:20:56.280 --> 00:20:59.710
None of these produce anything
recognizable as a modern cell.

00:20:59.710 --> 00:21:02.300
So this is a story, this
is historical science.

00:21:02.300 --> 00:21:05.050
And we may never be able to
tell fully the story of how

00:21:05.050 --> 00:21:07.050
life on Earth started uniquely.

00:21:07.050 --> 00:21:10.220
And we may have
to just face that.

00:21:10.220 --> 00:21:12.570
Life on Earth is telling us
something else about what

00:21:12.570 --> 00:21:13.910
to expect in the universe.

00:21:13.910 --> 00:21:16.880
And that's by looking at the
boundaries of life on Earth.

00:21:16.880 --> 00:21:18.550
So we kind of are
proud of ourselves

00:21:18.550 --> 00:21:20.120
because we can live most places.

00:21:20.120 --> 00:21:21.030
We live in Alaska.

00:21:21.030 --> 00:21:23.690
We live in the desert
here and so on.

00:21:23.690 --> 00:21:26.700
But basically, we're
ridiculously frail wusses.

00:21:26.700 --> 00:21:28.430
We're just pathetic.

00:21:28.430 --> 00:21:31.110
Life on Earth is much
more hardy than we are.

00:21:31.110 --> 00:21:33.970
And the hardiness is
all in microbial hands.

00:21:33.970 --> 00:21:36.050
So there are small
microorganisms

00:21:36.050 --> 00:21:38.410
that live-- you may
say life needs water,

00:21:38.410 --> 00:21:40.280
but life lives in
places where it

00:21:40.280 --> 00:21:43.810
hasn't rained for 100 years,
the high Atacama Desert.

00:21:43.810 --> 00:21:45.650
We imagine that
life needs water.

00:21:45.650 --> 00:21:48.750
But life can actually invent
its own kind of antifreeze

00:21:48.750 --> 00:21:51.460
and so exists quite happily
below the freezing point

00:21:51.460 --> 00:21:52.710
of water.

00:21:52.710 --> 00:21:55.750
Life can exist above the
boiling point of water too.

00:21:55.750 --> 00:21:58.850
And entire ecosystems were
found near hydrothermal vents

00:21:58.850 --> 00:22:01.900
in the 1970s in total
darkness at pressures

00:22:01.900 --> 00:22:05.590
of hundreds of atmospheres,
super heated water

00:22:05.590 --> 00:22:07.870
and at some level
independent of sunlight.

00:22:07.870 --> 00:22:10.800
So saying that life needs
a star is clearly wrong,

00:22:10.800 --> 00:22:13.280
because all it needs is an
energy source, in this case,

00:22:13.280 --> 00:22:15.490
geothermal energy.

00:22:15.490 --> 00:22:18.570
Life can handle incredible
radiation doses.

00:22:18.570 --> 00:22:21.530
This is deinococcus
radiodurans, which could happily

00:22:21.530 --> 00:22:25.690
absorb 1,000 times the radiation
dose that would drop us dead,

00:22:25.690 --> 00:22:28.160
stone dead, in
about five seconds.

00:22:28.160 --> 00:22:32.130
And it does so by keeping
stacked copies of its DNA

00:22:32.130 --> 00:22:35.700
to repair its DNA at a rate
hundreds or thousands of times

00:22:35.700 --> 00:22:37.480
faster than we can.

00:22:37.480 --> 00:22:39.400
So these are all
adaptations of life,

00:22:39.400 --> 00:22:43.490
which is permeated almost every
conceivable ecological niche

00:22:43.490 --> 00:22:46.920
on the Earth, and maybe
some that are inconceivable.

00:22:46.920 --> 00:22:49.880
Life has been found--
rich, diverse,

00:22:49.880 --> 00:22:52.660
microbial cultures have
been found in mines

00:22:52.660 --> 00:22:55.030
that were closed by the EPA.

00:22:55.030 --> 00:22:58.230
They have toxic run-off,
cadmium, mercury, silver,

00:22:58.230 --> 00:23:01.120
very, very toxic
heavy elements to us.

00:23:01.120 --> 00:23:03.100
But microbes can
metabolize these.

00:23:03.100 --> 00:23:04.880
They can gain their
energy from them.

00:23:04.880 --> 00:23:06.630
And they exist
quite happily, also

00:23:06.630 --> 00:23:09.040
with other extreme
conditions of high salinity

00:23:09.040 --> 00:23:12.880
or acidity, super
heated water, and so on.

00:23:12.880 --> 00:23:17.620
And then surprises continue, a
few years ago, a small microbe

00:23:17.620 --> 00:23:19.970
was found deep in a
mine in South Africa.

00:23:19.970 --> 00:23:22.210
It appears to be
an ecosystem of one

00:23:22.210 --> 00:23:26.080
living in the bathe radiation
glow of a totally dark mine

00:23:26.080 --> 00:23:27.290
shaft.

00:23:27.290 --> 00:23:28.670
And there are some
estimates that

00:23:28.670 --> 00:23:32.390
say that 90% of the
biomass of this planet

00:23:32.390 --> 00:23:35.600
is indeed below the Earth's
surface in microbial forms,

00:23:35.600 --> 00:23:37.605
perhaps like this.

00:23:37.605 --> 00:23:39.480
So that's a context for
life in the universe.

00:23:39.480 --> 00:23:41.970
And not all of these are
tiny and may be a little

00:23:41.970 --> 00:23:43.480
uninteresting to us, microbes.

00:23:43.480 --> 00:23:45.680
Here's an extremophile,
as they're called,

00:23:45.680 --> 00:23:46.650
which is visible.

00:23:46.650 --> 00:23:47.609
It's pretty small.

00:23:47.609 --> 00:23:50.150
It's about the size of the head
of a pin or a little smaller.

00:23:50.150 --> 00:23:53.210
It's a tardigrade, known
to children as water bear.

00:23:53.210 --> 00:23:55.730
And there are 700
different species of it.

00:23:55.730 --> 00:23:57.100
It has its own phylum.

00:23:57.100 --> 00:23:59.580
And it's quite a
complex organism.

00:23:59.580 --> 00:24:02.170
It has this amazing
trick of cryptobiosis,

00:24:02.170 --> 00:24:05.620
going into a freeze dried state
and rolling into a little ball

00:24:05.620 --> 00:24:08.310
where it can be carried on
the wind or an animal fur.

00:24:08.310 --> 00:24:11.080
And the chemistry, the
biochemistry, of this process

00:24:11.080 --> 00:24:14.860
is being studied in labs as
a way of learning perhaps

00:24:14.860 --> 00:24:17.750
how we might get suspended
animation as something that we

00:24:17.750 --> 00:24:20.270
can do to ourselves.

00:24:20.270 --> 00:24:22.420
So pulling some of
these things together,

00:24:22.420 --> 00:24:24.590
what is the
expectation in advance

00:24:24.590 --> 00:24:27.650
of finding life anywhere
else-- remember,

00:24:27.650 --> 00:24:30.090
it hasn't been found--
that life will be common?

00:24:30.090 --> 00:24:33.280
We'd have to have some reason
for that level of confidence

00:24:33.280 --> 00:24:35.920
without any evidence whatsoever.

00:24:35.920 --> 00:24:37.560
And the reasons are here.

00:24:37.560 --> 00:24:39.866
First, that life appeared
very early in the history

00:24:39.866 --> 00:24:41.490
of the Earth, when
the earth was really

00:24:41.490 --> 00:24:44.210
a very inhospitable place
with impact [? SEAM ?]

00:24:44.210 --> 00:24:46.460
rates thousands of
times what they are now,

00:24:46.460 --> 00:24:49.440
intense vulcanism, an
unbreathable atmosphere,

00:24:49.440 --> 00:24:50.350
life began.

00:24:50.350 --> 00:24:54.030
The motor of life ticked
over very, very early indeed.

00:24:54.030 --> 00:24:55.840
We know that the
basic ingredients

00:24:55.840 --> 00:24:58.560
can combine to form the
next level of ingredients,

00:24:58.560 --> 00:25:01.140
even if we can't
tell all that story.

00:25:01.140 --> 00:25:03.040
And then the
extremophiles tell us

00:25:03.040 --> 00:25:05.460
that given the
physical boundaries,

00:25:05.460 --> 00:25:07.850
the physical conditions
that bound life on Earth,

00:25:07.850 --> 00:25:10.920
it is expanded to fill almost
all of those conditions.

00:25:10.920 --> 00:25:12.740
It doesn't just go
for the happy middle

00:25:12.740 --> 00:25:15.240
or the comfortable
place, not like us.

00:25:15.240 --> 00:25:17.940
We want a nice beach
house in Hawaii.

00:25:17.940 --> 00:25:18.920
And then we're happy.

00:25:18.920 --> 00:25:20.810
We don't want to go
to those hard places.

00:25:20.810 --> 00:25:23.590
Well, life goes to the
hard places and does fine.

00:25:23.590 --> 00:25:25.360
We know the ingredients
are everywhere.

00:25:25.360 --> 00:25:28.220
And as I'll talk about,
there are abundant sights

00:25:28.220 --> 00:25:29.870
where life might form.

00:25:29.870 --> 00:25:30.840
So everything's there.

00:25:30.840 --> 00:25:33.780
It's like the table is set
in the universe for life.

00:25:33.780 --> 00:25:37.547
And now we want to know
if anyone's at the dinner.

00:25:37.547 --> 00:25:39.380
Let's start in the solar
system, the nearest

00:25:39.380 --> 00:25:42.080
place we can look in
some level of detail.

00:25:42.080 --> 00:25:44.090
And of course, we start
with the place we've

00:25:44.090 --> 00:25:46.220
looked most closely, Mars.

00:25:46.220 --> 00:25:49.650
