Earth will make a signal
100 times smaller, so

00:40:50.070 --> 00:40:51.320
a hundredth of a percent.

00:40:51.320 --> 00:40:53.190
And that sounds hard,
but that can be done.

00:40:53.190 --> 00:40:55.510
And that's what the Kepler
satellite was designed for.

00:40:55.510 --> 00:40:57.550
And I'll show you the
results from that.

00:40:57.550 --> 00:40:59.930
So this has become a
very powerful technique

00:40:59.930 --> 00:41:02.597
for not only measuring planets
and finding their mass,

00:41:02.597 --> 00:41:04.680
but also the size of the
planet, because the depth

00:41:04.680 --> 00:41:07.490
of the eclipse tells you
the size of the planet.

00:41:07.490 --> 00:41:10.720
And size plus a mass
gives you a density.

00:41:10.720 --> 00:41:13.209
So you learn something extra.

00:41:13.209 --> 00:41:14.750
And what we've
learned is that nature

00:41:14.750 --> 00:41:16.960
makes an extraordinary
variety of planets.

00:41:16.960 --> 00:41:19.860
Almost everything that
theorists could hypothesize

00:41:19.860 --> 00:41:21.430
has been found at this point.

00:41:21.430 --> 00:41:24.000
We've not really found
pure water planets.

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:27.050
But we've found planets
that are probably 50% or 60%

00:41:27.050 --> 00:41:29.040
water ice and the rest rocks.

00:41:29.040 --> 00:41:32.310
We found planets that
are 80% or 85% metal,

00:41:32.310 --> 00:41:33.860
mixed in with little rock.

00:41:33.860 --> 00:41:37.010
So extraordinary composition
variations of planets.

00:41:37.010 --> 00:41:39.120
And indeed many are
just like the sun

00:41:39.120 --> 00:41:41.400
and are mostly
hydrogen and helium.

00:41:41.400 --> 00:41:43.440
So it's a kind of a
wild world out there.

00:41:43.440 --> 00:41:45.510
And the level of
information is not always

00:41:45.510 --> 00:41:47.200
what we might want
to discriminate

00:41:47.200 --> 00:41:49.510
between these possibilities.

00:41:49.510 --> 00:41:51.330
The goal, of course,
is to detect earths.

00:41:51.330 --> 00:41:52.770
That's when it gets interesting.

00:41:52.770 --> 00:41:55.280
So let me give you the
state of that game.

00:41:55.280 --> 00:41:57.170
Here's what simulations tell us.

00:41:57.170 --> 00:41:59.250
This is a simulation
where things

00:41:59.250 --> 00:42:00.740
that are hundredth
the Earth mass,

00:42:00.740 --> 00:42:03.310
planetesimals, are
gradually glomming together

00:42:03.310 --> 00:42:05.690
by gravity, just by simple
accretion of running

00:42:05.690 --> 00:42:07.890
into each other and
sticking by gravity,

00:42:07.890 --> 00:42:10.930
into a small number
of large things.

00:42:10.930 --> 00:42:14.560
And so this is a simulation,
a full gravity simulation.

00:42:14.560 --> 00:42:17.770
And you can see how quickly,
starting from small chunks,

00:42:17.770 --> 00:42:20.350
you build up the
Earth-like planets.

00:42:20.350 --> 00:42:22.510
This is a simulation,
of course, and it's not

00:42:22.510 --> 00:42:25.450
expected that you generate
the inner solar system.

00:42:25.450 --> 00:42:28.360
But you can run this simulation
hundreds or thousands of times

00:42:28.360 --> 00:42:30.600
and see the diversity
of terrestrial planets.

00:42:30.600 --> 00:42:33.850
And what you find when you
run all these simulations is

00:42:33.850 --> 00:42:35.570
pretty much what you see here.

00:42:35.570 --> 00:42:38.100
That in general you
get between 2 and 5

00:42:38.100 --> 00:42:39.980
rocky terrestrial planets.

00:42:39.980 --> 00:42:43.780
And typically 10% to 20% of
them are in the habitable zones

00:42:43.780 --> 00:42:45.370
of their stars.

00:42:45.370 --> 00:42:47.990
So simulation, pure
theory, is telling

00:42:47.990 --> 00:42:52.270
you should expect essentially
all sun-like stars to have

00:42:52.270 --> 00:42:55.590
a couple of rocky
planets and 10% roughly

00:42:55.590 --> 00:42:57.350
of them to be in
the habitable zone

00:42:57.350 --> 00:42:59.700
and therefore potentially
have liquid water.

00:42:59.700 --> 00:43:00.890
So a very exciting number.

00:43:00.890 --> 00:43:01.800
But that's theory.

00:43:01.800 --> 00:43:03.450
What does the data say?

00:43:03.450 --> 00:43:06.230
Here's the data from just
a month ago from the Kepler

00:43:06.230 --> 00:43:08.700
satellite finally releasing
Earth-like planets

00:43:08.700 --> 00:43:10.010
for the first time.

00:43:10.010 --> 00:43:12.500
So you saw the 15-year
history of this object

00:43:12.500 --> 00:43:14.260
until a month ago.

00:43:14.260 --> 00:43:16.890
Here's the data that NASA
released in a press conference

00:43:16.890 --> 00:43:18.400
quite recently.

00:43:18.400 --> 00:43:20.620
Kepler is looking for
these small eclipses.

00:43:20.620 --> 00:43:22.980
And because it can detect
a very subtle eclipse,

00:43:22.980 --> 00:43:23.970
it can find earths.

00:43:23.970 --> 00:43:25.940
And the proof is right here.

00:43:25.940 --> 00:43:29.110
But Kepler has only been
working for a few months.

00:43:29.110 --> 00:43:32.300
And so these Earth-like
planets are, of course,

00:43:32.300 --> 00:43:35.850
in orbital periods of a
month, maybe two months.

00:43:35.850 --> 00:43:38.490
So they're going around their
stars faster than mercury.

00:43:38.490 --> 00:43:40.660
And so they're
hotter than Mercury.

00:43:40.660 --> 00:43:41.950
So we have to be patient.

00:43:41.950 --> 00:43:44.860
We have to wait until Kepler
has worked for a couple of years

00:43:44.860 --> 00:43:47.650
before it can find an Earth
in an Earth-like orbit.

00:43:47.650 --> 00:43:50.310
But this tells you that
they're there to be found.

00:43:50.310 --> 00:43:53.980
We just have to be patient for
the satellite to bring them in.

00:43:53.980 --> 00:43:56.260
And the other exciting
thing from these results

00:43:56.260 --> 00:43:58.930
is that the number of
planets increases rapidly

00:43:58.930 --> 00:44:00.600
towards the detection limit.

00:44:00.600 --> 00:44:03.200
So for every Jupiter
or Saturn-like planet,

00:44:03.200 --> 00:44:06.270
you actually expect
many Earth-like planets.

00:44:06.270 --> 00:44:08.330
Rocky, terrestrial
planets are abundant.

00:44:08.330 --> 00:44:10.790
They're not rare at all.

00:44:10.790 --> 00:44:12.800
Going back to simulations,
the simulations

00:44:12.800 --> 00:44:15.280
allow us to follow the
water in a simulation.

00:44:15.280 --> 00:44:18.600
So we can see where these rocky
planets what water content they

00:44:18.600 --> 00:44:19.450
have.

00:44:19.450 --> 00:44:21.810
And you might think the
Earth is a water planet.

00:44:21.810 --> 00:44:23.150
We think the Earth is special.

00:44:23.150 --> 00:44:24.900
We talk about it
as the water world

00:44:24.900 --> 00:44:26.880
and think that it's
special for that reason.

00:44:26.880 --> 00:44:29.990
And certainly Mars is
dry and Venus baked dry.

00:44:29.990 --> 00:44:32.760
But these simulations
tell us that, in general,

00:44:32.760 --> 00:44:35.490
terrestrial planets will
have as much as the inventory

00:44:35.490 --> 00:44:37.820
of the Earth's oceans,
maybe even 10 times as much,

00:44:37.820 --> 00:44:39.730
maybe 100 times as much.

00:44:39.730 --> 00:44:42.320
Remember, water is not
of rare ingredient.

00:44:42.320 --> 00:44:43.910
So we have everything we need.

00:44:43.910 --> 00:44:46.050
We have abundant,
rocky planets beginning

00:44:46.050 --> 00:44:47.630
to be found by Kepler.

00:44:47.630 --> 00:44:50.840
We have some fraction of
them, a significant fraction,

00:44:50.840 --> 00:44:54.290
in a habitable zone where liquid
water can be on the surface.

00:44:54.290 --> 00:44:56.990
And models tell us that that
liquid water will be there.

00:44:56.990 --> 00:44:59.420
It will be part of the
composition of the planet.

00:44:59.420 --> 00:45:00.490
It's very exciting.

00:45:00.490 --> 00:45:04.386
It's just a matter of time
before we pull in an Earth.

00:45:04.386 --> 00:45:05.760
What's the next
step of the game?

00:45:05.760 --> 00:45:07.426
The next step of the
game is, of course,

00:45:07.426 --> 00:45:09.100
to look for signs for life.

00:45:09.100 --> 00:45:11.590
These planets are dozens
of light years away.

00:45:11.590 --> 00:45:15.160
They're impossibly faint to
observe with our telescopes.

00:45:15.160 --> 00:45:20.120
The best we can do is take that
feeble light a billion times

00:45:20.120 --> 00:45:24.170
fainter than the star it orbits
and spread it into a spectrum

00:45:24.170 --> 00:45:26.600
and try and look for what
are called biomarkers.

00:45:26.600 --> 00:45:29.090
That is the signatures
and spectroscopy

00:45:29.090 --> 00:45:32.120
of elements we think are
connected with biology.

00:45:32.120 --> 00:45:35.340
So you can see from the
comparison with Mars and Venus,

00:45:35.340 --> 00:45:37.900
where the major imprint in
their atmosphere in the infrared

00:45:37.900 --> 00:45:40.490
is carbon dioxide
from the atmosphere.

00:45:40.490 --> 00:45:42.230
Earth has that imprint too.

00:45:42.230 --> 00:45:44.860
But it has the extra
signature of ozone.

00:45:44.860 --> 00:45:47.562
It's a stronger
signal than water

00:45:47.562 --> 00:45:48.770
it turns out in the infrared.

00:45:48.770 --> 00:45:50.380
That's what you look for.

00:45:50.380 --> 00:45:52.190
And, of course, it has water.

00:45:52.190 --> 00:45:53.890
And ozone is a biomarker.

00:45:53.890 --> 00:45:55.290
Oxygen is a biomarker.

00:45:55.290 --> 00:45:58.540
Methane, much of which is
produced by biology on Earth

00:45:58.540 --> 00:46:01.620
in our atmosphere at a
trace level, is a biomarker.

00:46:01.620 --> 00:46:03.740
This is the next
stage of the game,

00:46:03.740 --> 00:46:07.050
to take the best of those
Earths and use our very biggest

00:46:07.050 --> 00:46:09.030
telescopes on the
ground and in space--

00:46:09.030 --> 00:46:11.320
this is very light
hungry, this kind of work.

00:46:11.320 --> 00:46:14.030
It's why we're building
the GMT down in Chile.

00:46:14.030 --> 00:46:17.100
It's why we built the
LBT interferometer here

00:46:17.100 --> 00:46:19.360
on Mount Graham is to
do this kind of work.

00:46:19.360 --> 00:46:21.520
It's why the James
Webb Space Telescope

00:46:21.520 --> 00:46:24.339
is being planned to succeed
the Hubble Space Telescope.

00:46:24.339 --> 00:46:25.880
All of these big
facilities are going

00:46:25.880 --> 00:46:28.000
to do this kind of science.

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:29.590
And that's going to
be the next step.

00:46:29.590 --> 00:46:32.410
And that may be indeed in
the next five to 10 years

00:46:32.410 --> 00:46:36.030
how we learn that we think
we found a terrestrial planet

00:46:36.030 --> 00:46:38.200
with the signature of biology.

00:46:38.200 --> 00:46:40.720
Remember, on the Earth, if
life disappeared overnight,

00:46:40.720 --> 00:46:43.450
if biosphere went
dead overnight,

00:46:43.450 --> 00:46:46.450
the 20% of the air you're
breathing that's oxygen

00:46:46.450 --> 00:46:48.665
would disappear in a
million years, which

00:46:48.665 --> 00:46:52.330
is geologically a blink of an
eye, because oxygen, of course,

00:46:52.330 --> 00:46:53.590
is very reactive.

00:46:53.590 --> 00:46:56.350
It will just rust everything
and go into seawater and so on.

00:46:56.350 --> 00:47:00.440
And so oxygen is only maintained
on a planetary time scale

00:47:00.440 --> 00:47:02.450
by biology, in our experience.

00:47:02.450 --> 00:47:05.670
And that's why we think
it's a good biomarker.

00:47:05.670 --> 00:47:08.010
Just to put a little
sobering thought on this.

00:47:08.010 --> 00:47:10.080
We might think, oh, great
we'll have an Earth.

00:47:10.080 --> 00:47:13.470
That will be a place where
can go in case things

00:47:13.470 --> 00:47:14.510
go south here.

00:47:14.510 --> 00:47:16.220
No, I don't think so.

00:47:16.220 --> 00:47:19.199
Well, Earth 2.0 is not going
to be exactly like Earth.

00:47:19.199 --> 00:47:20.990
When we talk about
Earth clones, of course,

00:47:20.990 --> 00:47:25.170
we're talking about
similar, not identical.

00:47:25.170 --> 00:47:27.140
And I don't think
any of it relieves us

00:47:27.140 --> 00:47:28.840
of the need to take
care of our planet,

00:47:28.840 --> 00:47:32.780
because these nearest Earth-like
planets are likely from Kepler

00:47:32.780 --> 00:47:35.870
to be actually dozens of light,
maybe even hundreds or 200

00:47:35.870 --> 00:47:36.950
light years away.

00:47:36.950 --> 00:47:39.390
There is no way we
are ever going there

00:47:39.390 --> 00:47:41.070
in any conceivable time scale.

00:47:41.070 --> 00:47:43.410
They're beyond our
reach for travel,

00:47:43.410 --> 00:47:48.420
for colonization, for voyaging,
even for joyrides in the future

00:47:48.420 --> 00:47:49.950
that any of us can see.

00:47:49.950 --> 00:47:52.840
So we've got to look
after this planet.

00:47:52.840 --> 00:47:55.390
So that's the state of
the game for microbes.

00:47:55.390 --> 00:47:57.635
That's where we think
we'll look for--

00:47:57.635 --> 00:48:00.750
[SNORING]

00:48:00.750 --> 00:48:02.690
Oh, OK, microbes, who cares?

00:48:02.690 --> 00:48:05.430
Now come on, it's pond scum.

00:48:05.430 --> 00:48:07.720
It's the stuff you scrape
off your shower curtain.

00:48:07.720 --> 00:48:09.030
It's yeast.

00:48:09.030 --> 00:48:10.600
Please.

00:48:10.600 --> 00:48:12.105
Why am I boring you with this?

00:48:12.105 --> 00:48:14.230
This is not what life in
the universe is about.

00:48:14.230 --> 00:48:16.350
Life in the universe
is about companionship.

00:48:16.350 --> 00:48:17.450
It's about, are we alone?

00:48:17.450 --> 00:48:18.390
Let's get real here.

00:48:18.390 --> 00:48:20.250
OK, now I'm going to get real.

00:48:20.250 --> 00:48:22.410
Where are the aliens?

00:48:22.410 --> 00:48:24.590
OK, let's get to the real thing.

00:48:24.590 --> 00:48:27.190
I've done that crappy
boring science stuff.

00:48:27.190 --> 00:48:29.110
You know, OK, this is
how we find microbes.

00:48:29.110 --> 00:48:30.980
But we really are
going to do it.

00:48:30.980 --> 00:48:32.929
Now let's go up the chain a bit.

00:48:32.929 --> 00:48:35.220
But I'm still going to stay
with microbes a little bit,

00:48:35.220 --> 00:48:37.010
because microbes should
get dissed a lot.

00:48:37.010 --> 00:48:39.760
You know, microbes are kind
of interesting, even for me

00:48:39.760 --> 00:48:41.700
as a kind of physical scientist.

00:48:41.700 --> 00:48:44.970
So we tend to underestimate--
we think we're very smart

00:48:44.970 --> 00:48:46.720
and we have technology
and all that stuff.

00:48:46.720 --> 00:48:49.390
But if we're starting to
look for intelligent life

00:48:49.390 --> 00:48:50.890
in the universe,
high functioning,

00:48:50.890 --> 00:48:53.817
technological life,
life with brains,

00:48:53.817 --> 00:48:55.400
we've got to get our
reference points.

00:48:55.400 --> 00:48:58.270
And once again, the Earth
is our reference point.

00:48:58.270 --> 00:49:00.300
And I'll just make
the obvious comment

00:49:00.300 --> 00:49:03.470
that microbes have figured
out some pretty clever things,

00:49:03.470 --> 00:49:05.310
like they figured out
how to make nanowires

00:49:05.310 --> 00:49:06.770
before we ever did in a lab.

00:49:06.770 --> 00:49:08.100
They can sense magnetic fields.

00:49:08.100 --> 00:49:11.690
They can operate commensally
and in cooperation.

00:49:11.690 --> 00:49:14.435
They can exchange signals
with reasonable bit

00:49:14.435 --> 00:49:17.600
rates, some forms of
chemical communication.

00:49:17.600 --> 00:49:19.130
That's pretty clever.

00:49:19.130 --> 00:49:21.200
If you go up the
chain a bit to things

00:49:21.200 --> 00:49:24.390
that are beneath your
contempt, for the most part,

00:49:24.390 --> 00:49:27.019
you might notice that
termites build mounds

00:49:27.019 --> 00:49:28.560
that scale to
[? SEAM ?] the organism

00:49:28.560 --> 00:49:30.960
are bigger than our
tallest skyscrapers.

00:49:30.960 --> 00:49:33.630
And they have five different
temperature control mechanisms

00:49:33.630 --> 00:49:36.490
built into the composites
of natural substances

00:49:36.490 --> 00:49:39.550
that they put together
to make these things.

00:49:39.550 --> 00:49:40.880
That's pretty cool.

00:49:40.880 --> 00:49:42.960
And social insects,
obviously, you

00:49:42.960 --> 00:49:45.166
can just say they're all
hardwired by evolution

00:49:45.166 --> 00:49:47.040
and they don't have any
choice in the matter.

00:49:47.040 --> 00:49:49.080
But viewed from afar,
again, if you're

00:49:49.080 --> 00:49:51.170
trying to distinguish
intelligence

00:49:51.170 --> 00:49:54.490
and non-intelligence,
it's not an easy call,

00:49:54.490 --> 00:49:58.120
because they do have
stratification of communication

00:49:58.120 --> 00:49:59.840
and highly organized
functioning that

00:49:59.840 --> 00:50:03.270
is adaptive to their
situation, their environment.

00:50:03.270 --> 00:50:07.240
And I think the point is
not whether ants or termites

00:50:07.240 --> 00:50:08.860
or social insects are smart.

00:50:08.860 --> 00:50:11.190
The question is that evolution
does not stand still.

00:50:11.190 --> 00:50:14.670
We view the natural
world and the organisms

00:50:14.670 --> 00:50:16.880
we share the planet with
at a snapshot of time,

00:50:16.880 --> 00:50:18.640
where we happen to
be king of the hill

00:50:18.640 --> 00:50:20.264
and we are able to
look down on them

00:50:20.264 --> 00:50:22.930
and say, well, yeah that's fine,
but you don't have cell phones.

00:50:22.930 --> 00:50:24.810
Come on, please.

00:50:24.810 --> 00:50:27.020
Please come back when you
have wireless internet

00:50:27.020 --> 00:50:28.270
and then we'll talk.

00:50:28.270 --> 00:50:30.830
You are not
sophisticated, please.

00:50:30.830 --> 00:50:32.830
So that's what we think about.

00:50:32.830 --> 00:50:35.810
But the truth is evolution
doesn't stand still.

00:50:35.810 --> 00:50:37.800
If we screw up
this planet, which

00:50:37.800 --> 00:50:39.790
we're sort of doing
in the margins

00:50:39.790 --> 00:50:42.690
and we're not here in a
million years, fair bet,

00:50:42.690 --> 00:50:45.610
I want to see what insects
have done in 100 million years.

00:50:45.610 --> 00:50:48.480
Remember, there's many, many
millions of species of them.

00:50:48.480 --> 00:50:50.760
There's more of them
than there are of us.

00:50:50.760 --> 00:50:54.810
And they're doing their thing
quite happily and quite nicely.

00:50:54.810 --> 00:50:56.600
And, of course, you
talk about technology.

00:50:56.600 --> 00:50:58.650
Let me just diminish that
envelope a little bit.

00:50:58.650 --> 00:51:00.191
Technology, yeah,
we have technology.

00:51:00.191 --> 00:51:03.100
And sure we have the
technology I just alluded to.

00:51:03.100 --> 00:51:05.730
But if you're talking about
technology as life's solution

00:51:05.730 --> 00:51:07.840
to problems, then that's
pretty impressive.

00:51:07.840 --> 00:51:10.860
You make a list of things that
animals and sometimes very

00:51:10.860 --> 00:51:14.070
small animals, 100 million years
ago, invented before we did,

00:51:14.070 --> 00:51:16.910
it includes flight,
sonar, magnetic sensing,

00:51:16.910 --> 00:51:18.996
infrared sensing, batteries,
polarization sense,

00:51:18.996 --> 00:51:21.240
fiber optics, holography.

00:51:21.240 --> 00:51:22.676
I could make an
even longer list.

00:51:22.676 --> 00:51:24.300
And you might say,
well, yeah, but they

00:51:24.300 --> 00:51:27.270
weren't doing it in
labs and with inventions

00:51:27.270 --> 00:51:30.230
and wearing white
coats and stuff.

00:51:30.230 --> 00:51:31.380
But that's OK.

00:51:31.380 --> 00:51:33.860
They just did it.

00:51:33.860 --> 00:51:35.786
And then you work
up the chain a bit

00:51:35.786 --> 00:51:37.660
and you get maybe the
things that we actually

00:51:37.660 --> 00:51:39.340
consider as pets.

00:51:39.340 --> 00:51:41.480
You know, so they're
creatures that can talk.

00:51:41.480 --> 00:51:43.800
Creatures that have behaviors
that look interesting.

00:51:43.800 --> 00:51:46.710
Alex the parrot, connection
to the U of A there,

00:51:46.710 --> 00:51:49.860
talkative and playful able to
understand the concept of zero,

00:51:49.860 --> 00:51:54.690
which not all humans can do.

00:51:54.690 --> 00:51:58.340
Rats, ticklish and curious,
personality traits.

00:51:58.340 --> 00:52:01.200
Rats can anticipate sex and
some very beautiful experiments

00:52:01.200 --> 00:52:04.220
a decade ago show that they can
reflect on their own thinking.

00:52:04.220 --> 00:52:06.330
Metacognition is
quite a high skill.

00:52:06.330 --> 00:52:10.310
So maybe we shouldn't
rodents completely.

00:52:10.310 --> 00:52:11.845
But you've probably seen this.

00:52:11.845 --> 00:52:14.570
This is a crow, never been
in this situation before,

00:52:14.570 --> 00:52:16.320
Caledonian crow called Betty.

00:52:16.320 --> 00:52:17.140
They like meat.

00:52:17.140 --> 00:52:18.870
And there's meat in a basket.

00:52:18.870 --> 00:52:19.960
She has a wire.

00:52:19.960 --> 00:52:21.740
But it's a straight wire.

00:52:21.740 --> 00:52:23.620
There happens to be a
notch cut in the base

00:52:23.620 --> 00:52:25.750
of the thing holding the tube.

00:52:25.750 --> 00:52:29.734
Again, never been in this
situation, first time.

00:52:29.734 --> 00:52:33.750
They use stick in the
wild, but not wire.

00:52:33.750 --> 00:52:35.630
She figures she can
turn that into a lever.

00:52:40.710 --> 00:52:45.820
That's a real time experiment
and quite impressive.

00:52:45.820 --> 00:52:49.310
So that maybe the adjective
birdbrain is a perjorative.

00:52:53.640 --> 00:52:56.360
And then we have creatures
that separated us

00:52:56.360 --> 00:52:58.440
from the tree of life
in the tree of life

00:52:58.440 --> 00:53:00.760
hundreds of millions
of years ago

00:53:00.760 --> 00:53:02.740
and that have
extraordinary capabilities.

00:53:02.740 --> 00:53:06.450
Cephalopods are shape
shifting creatures

00:53:06.450 --> 00:53:08.250
with distributed
brains, where there's

00:53:08.250 --> 00:53:11.080
a central brain and a
brain located on each arm.

00:53:11.080 --> 00:53:14.940
If the arm is
severed, the arm will

00:53:14.940 --> 00:53:20.670
continue to move and camouflage
to distract the predator.

00:53:20.670 --> 00:53:22.550
We just don't know how
smart these creatures.

00:53:22.550 --> 00:53:25.840
I've talked to divers who have
been led on wild goose chases

00:53:25.840 --> 00:53:28.810
through the complex three
dimensional topology of a coral

00:53:28.810 --> 00:53:31.440
reef basically
getting the diver lost

00:53:31.440 --> 00:53:33.800
and then coming and
retrieving the diver again.

00:53:33.800 --> 00:53:35.550
We can't communicate
with these creatures.

00:53:35.550 --> 00:53:36.050
That's all.

00:53:36.050 --> 00:53:39.100
So these are the aliens that
we co-exist with on the planet.

00:53:39.100 --> 00:53:40.810
Maybe we should try
and understand them

00:53:40.810 --> 00:53:44.420
first before we see
what we get out there.

00:53:44.420 --> 00:53:46.750
And in terms of the ratio
of brain mass to body mass,

00:53:46.750 --> 00:53:47.500
we're special.

00:53:47.500 --> 00:53:49.420
But we're not like
off the chart.

00:53:49.420 --> 00:53:52.170
And some of these small
brains are very, very well

00:53:52.170 --> 00:53:54.930
put together packages.

00:53:54.930 --> 00:53:56.810
So you go up to
something like an orca,

00:53:56.810 --> 00:53:58.860
and it's a pretty close call.

00:53:58.860 --> 00:54:00.060
No natural enemies.

00:54:00.060 --> 00:54:02.040
We're their only enemy.

00:54:02.040 --> 00:54:04.700
Large brains, complex
brains, languages.

00:54:04.700 --> 00:54:07.000
The orca pods in
the Puget Sound have

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:10.380
dialects not only at the level
of different pods and sub-pods,

00:54:10.380 --> 00:54:12.470
but of family members,
individual family

00:54:12.470 --> 00:54:14.960
members or familial groupings.

00:54:14.960 --> 00:54:17.715
They are social animals
that raise their young

00:54:17.715 --> 00:54:20.330
in the similar proportion
of their total lifespan

00:54:20.330 --> 00:54:22.000
to humans raising their young.

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:23.950
And then it starts
to get less clear.

00:54:23.950 --> 00:54:25.020
Orcas mate for life.

00:54:25.020 --> 00:54:26.840
Statistically we don't.

00:54:26.840 --> 00:54:29.850
And I think the
problem with them

00:54:29.850 --> 00:54:31.550
is they don't have
opposable thumbs

00:54:31.550 --> 00:54:34.817
and so they've never done
this wireless internet stuff.

00:54:34.817 --> 00:54:35.900
And they don't have bombs.

00:54:35.900 --> 00:54:36.900
And they don't have cars.

00:54:36.900 --> 00:54:38.108
That's not really their loss.

00:54:38.108 --> 00:54:40.500
They're supremely adapted
to their environment.

00:54:40.500 --> 00:54:43.290
But I'll make another point
about evolution and time.

00:54:43.290 --> 00:54:46.700
On the left you see the rise
in brain mass corresponding

00:54:46.700 --> 00:54:49.820
to the evolutionary surge that
took us to the top of the pile.

00:54:49.820 --> 00:54:52.260
Notice that happened over
the last two million years

00:54:52.260 --> 00:54:55.520
and in a real surge in
the last 100,000 years.

00:54:55.520 --> 00:54:59.000
That brain mass increase is now
plotted in terms of the ratio

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:02.360
to body mass on the right
and the track of the apes

00:55:02.360 --> 00:55:04.850
our ancestors and
that recent surge

00:55:04.850 --> 00:55:07.940
taking us to encephalization
quotient of 7

00:55:07.940 --> 00:55:10.350
on the right edge shown.

00:55:10.350 --> 00:55:12.180
And the point is
that an alien coming

00:55:12.180 --> 00:55:14.690
to this planet at almost
any time in the last 50

00:55:14.690 --> 00:55:18.230
million years and saying, take
me to the brainy creatures,

00:55:18.230 --> 00:55:20.820
would have gone to the
whales and the dolphins

00:55:20.820 --> 00:55:21.860
and their ancestors.

00:55:21.860 --> 00:55:24.020
It's a very recent
thing that we've

00:55:24.020 --> 00:55:27.560
become the most encephalized
creatures on Earth.

00:55:27.560 --> 00:55:30.160
So it doesn't stand still.

00:55:30.160 --> 00:55:32.890
It's a snapshot.

00:55:32.890 --> 00:55:35.700
And we don't know how this
plays out in the future.

00:55:35.700 --> 00:55:38.560
We have no idea how
evolution how will take us.

00:55:38.560 --> 00:55:40.040
Life on earth is already weird.

00:55:40.040 --> 00:55:42.660
There's some very weird life
that we've already discussed.

00:55:42.660 --> 00:55:45.510
I think in general we could
have levels of weirdness.

00:55:45.510 --> 00:55:47.520
At the macroscopic
level, we could really

00:55:47.520 --> 00:55:50.380
have different cell
types than we have now.

00:55:50.380 --> 00:55:53.440
We could have much more
rapid rates of evolution

00:55:53.440 --> 00:55:56.640
based on something that does
happen in life on Earth, which

00:55:56.640 --> 00:56:01.270
is swapping of genetic material
in packages, either organisms

00:56:01.270 --> 00:56:03.500
co-opting each other
or genetic swamping.

00:56:03.500 --> 00:56:07.480
It doesn't have to be the
slow march of mutation and DNA

00:56:07.480 --> 00:56:08.670
variation.

00:56:08.670 --> 00:56:10.150
And then I think
there's no reason

00:56:10.150 --> 00:56:11.566
the universe
couldn't have created

00:56:11.566 --> 00:56:12.960
something other than a cell.

00:56:12.960 --> 00:56:14.610
You don't need a cell
to have something

00:56:14.610 --> 00:56:16.280
that you might call
biology, except you

00:56:16.280 --> 00:56:17.482
won't call it biology.

00:56:17.482 --> 00:56:18.940
You could have a
network as opposed

00:56:18.940 --> 00:56:21.590
to a container that did
everything fundamentally

00:56:21.590 --> 00:56:23.040
that biology does.

00:56:23.040 --> 00:56:25.530
And then some of these
things could clearly scale up

00:56:25.530 --> 00:56:26.800
to the level of a planet.

00:56:26.800 --> 00:56:28.770
And you could have
geoengineering of a planet

00:56:28.770 --> 00:56:31.480
by creatures that might be
individually at the organism

00:56:31.480 --> 00:56:33.454
level quite small.

00:56:33.454 --> 00:56:35.120
If you're talking
about the micro level,

00:56:35.120 --> 00:56:36.453
there's also possible weirdness.

00:56:36.453 --> 00:56:39.820
A variation, a small variation
would be just changing

00:56:39.820 --> 00:56:41.370
the genetic code a little bit.

00:56:41.370 --> 00:56:42.570
But that's very mild.

00:56:42.570 --> 00:56:43.280
That's modest.

00:56:43.280 --> 00:56:44.540
Let's go beyond that.

00:56:44.540 --> 00:56:48.240
You could go away from the
central dogma of biology,

00:56:48.240 --> 00:56:50.850
the triad of DNA,
RNA, and proteins.

00:56:50.850 --> 00:56:53.160
Or you could go to
non-carbon based

00:56:53.160 --> 00:56:57.836
biology or not using water as
your solvent, as your medium.

00:56:57.836 --> 00:57:00.210
And then you could actually--
there's room at the bottom.

00:57:00.210 --> 00:57:03.480
Although a human
has a DVD's worth

00:57:03.480 --> 00:57:06.790
of information in it the genetic
code, that's pretty impressive.

00:57:06.790 --> 00:57:08.760
That's not the
limit of compactness

00:57:08.760 --> 00:57:11.350
biochemistry could
attain, in principle.

00:57:11.350 --> 00:57:13.430
Now, whether it happens
in practice, who knows?

00:57:13.430 --> 00:57:15.710
And so you could have even
higher density and perhaps

00:57:15.710 --> 00:57:18.810
a vastly speeded
up scale evolution

00:57:18.810 --> 00:57:20.570
with a totally different basis.

00:57:20.570 --> 00:57:24.100
So I'm obviously getting
wildly speculating here.

00:57:24.100 --> 00:57:27.680
But the point is for exobiology,
we don't know what to expect.

00:57:27.680 --> 00:57:30.070
And some of these
forms of life, we

00:57:30.070 --> 00:57:31.620
look at the conjunct
of things that

00:57:31.620 --> 00:57:34.420
use planets, that
use carbon, that use

00:57:34.420 --> 00:57:36.660
DNA as their genetic material.

00:57:36.660 --> 00:57:39.740
But the conjunct of those
might be unrecognizable

00:57:39.740 --> 00:57:43.850
if one of those things doesn't
apply or none of them apply.

00:57:43.850 --> 00:57:45.890
So let's just look a
little into the future

00:57:45.890 --> 00:57:47.770
because it's a
snapshot right now.

00:57:47.770 --> 00:57:50.897
So what might change?

00:57:50.897 --> 00:57:52.480
The singularity, as
you probably know,

00:57:52.480 --> 00:57:54.950
is a term invented by Ray
Kurzweil, actually not.

00:57:54.950 --> 00:57:55.750
He popularized it.

00:57:55.750 --> 00:57:57.840
It was invented before him.

00:57:57.840 --> 00:58:00.890
But it's a reference to the fact
that at our stage of evolution,

00:58:00.890 --> 00:58:02.610
we may pass through
a membrane where

00:58:02.610 --> 00:58:04.770
we become post biological.

00:58:04.770 --> 00:58:06.540
And once again, if
we're not special,

00:58:06.540 --> 00:58:08.500
if the Copernican
principle applies,

00:58:08.500 --> 00:58:10.750
that could have happened
elsewhere in the universe.

00:58:10.750 --> 00:58:14.160
And given the time available,
it may well have happened.

00:58:14.160 --> 00:58:17.140
And looking at
this, the increase

00:58:17.140 --> 00:58:19.930
of information in the
genetic form of evolution

00:58:19.930 --> 00:58:23.240
has been dwarfed by cultural
evolution, when we invented

00:58:23.240 --> 00:58:26.690
civilization and books,
and then dwarfed yet again

00:58:26.690 --> 00:58:30.160
by digital evolution,
our modern technology.

00:58:30.160 --> 00:58:34.050
So the rate of information,
encoding, transmittal,

00:58:34.050 --> 00:58:37.470
and growth is now 10
to 18 times higher

00:58:37.470 --> 00:58:40.050
than it is with biology
alone acting over time.

00:58:40.050 --> 00:58:42.390
That's an incredible
acceleration.

00:58:42.390 --> 00:58:46.540
If you project Moore's law and
its equivalence in networking,

00:58:46.540 --> 00:58:48.470
you actually get
to a position where

00:58:48.470 --> 00:58:50.314
you could approximate
the capacity

00:58:50.314 --> 00:58:54.350
in the human brain in terms of
network connections in about

00:58:54.350 --> 00:58:56.230
20 years.

00:58:56.230 --> 00:58:58.550
And remember, this was ENIAC.

00:58:58.550 --> 00:59:01.880
And this was a computer
a long time ago

00:59:01.880 --> 00:59:04.560
that was in the size of a
family home, took about a third

00:59:04.560 --> 00:59:06.230
of the power of
Philadelphia to run it,

00:59:06.230 --> 00:59:09.150
had five technicians
full-time changing valves.

00:59:09.150 --> 00:59:12.250
And this is 50 times
worse than whatever

00:59:12.250 --> 00:59:15.320
cell phone, smartphone
you have in your pocket.

00:59:15.320 --> 00:59:16.790
So things don't stand still.

00:59:16.790 --> 00:59:19.520
And what matters really is the
capacity of the total package,

00:59:19.520 --> 00:59:21.500
not just the processor.

00:59:21.500 --> 00:59:24.000
And so people with
robots have shown

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:28.710
how connecting simple machines
that have sensing capability

00:59:28.710 --> 00:59:30.390
and linking them
with a neural net,

00:59:30.390 --> 00:59:32.780
so it has the capacity
to self-program

00:59:32.780 --> 00:59:34.235
and to learn from
its environment,

00:59:34.235 --> 00:59:37.880
it's not intelligent, the
intelligence is not put in.

00:59:37.880 --> 00:59:40.083
It emerges from the base level.

00:59:40.083 --> 00:59:43.950
This creates some
interesting possibilities.

00:59:43.950 --> 00:59:45.890
It's machine intelligence,
but of course it's

00:59:45.890 --> 00:59:47.542
facilitated by humans.

00:59:51.190 --> 00:59:53.460
So after iterations
of this, again,

00:59:53.460 --> 00:59:55.010
these behaviors
are not programmed

00:59:55.010 --> 00:59:57.950
into the little robots at all.

